  "method": "We propose HILO: Hierarchical, Inspectable, Look-ahead Options. Stage 1 bootstraps a compact skill library and subgoal vocabulary. From a handful of demonstrations, we segment trajectories into near-atomic subskills (e.g., reach, grasp, place) and goal predicates by reverse-trajectory slicing; we mix these with self-generated rollouts using hindsight experience replay to train goal-conditioned, parameterized option policies π_i(a|s,g), termination β_i(s), and critics Q_i(s,g,a). For each skill, we also learn a success-probability head u_i(s,g) for fast feasibility tests. This yields reusable skills with standardized interfaces (initiation set, parameters g, termination, success estimate) and a predicate set that can describe nested subgoals.\n\nStage 2 equips each skill with a Skill Effect Model (SEM) and the agent with an explicit, factored world state. Each SEM f_i predicts the terminal state and cumulative cost of executing skill i with parameters g from state s; we implement f_i as an object-centric GNN that outputs per-object deltas and a graph-level cost. In parallel, a state reader/writer maintains a structured memory M_t of symbolic predicates (achieved subgoals, resource usage, temporal relations). After every transition (s_t, a_t, s_{t+1}), the writer updates M_{t+1}; the reader conditions both high-level choice and low-level controllers on M_t, enabling explicit tracking of nested goal completion and providing clean hooks for mid-trajectory supervision.\n\nStage 3 plans and executes in skill space with closed-loop replanning. Given (s_t, M_t) and a task goal, we perform a short-horizon look-ahead search over sequences of (skill, parameters) using the SEMs: sample skill candidates and continuous parameters, prune branches by u_i(s,g) thresholds, predict successor states with f_i, and score partial plans by the sum of expected costs and learned value-to-go. We use Weighted A* to balance exploitation and goal distance, and enrich the node score with the downstream critics ∑ Q_i to better capture local difficulty. The best branch yields the next option to execute; we run its low-level controller to termination, ingest real transitions to refine both π_i and f_i, update M, and then replan—keeping the plan reactive to model errors and stochasticity.\n\nStage 4 adds shaped credit and data-driven hierarchy refinement. We train a process-reward verifier that scores whether each executed step advanced the relevant subgoal(s) given (s_t, s_{t+1}, M_t), producing dense r_proc∈[0,1]. A composite return combines sparse outcome reward with these step-level signals, scaled higher on successful episodes to emphasize faithful processes without rewarding spurious progress. To further improve the high-level policy, we run a self-sampling tree: from shared prefixes, generate multiple candidate skill sequences, score their steps with the verifier, and derive preference pairs and listwise orderings. We then update a high-level selector network with a ranking loss that prefers plans and decisions yielding higher verifier scores and eventual success. Throughout training, we maintain an adaptive curriculum: resets are drawn near later subgoals early on and gradually move outward as success stabilizes, ensuring both options and the planner see appropriately staged difficulties.",
  "rationale": "HILO attacks long-horizon credit assignment by factoring the task along natural temporal abstractions and making subgoal progress measurable. Options localize gradient credit to short skill executions; SEMs let us plan over these options to leap across long horizons without incurring action-level exploration debt; and explicit state memory turns nested goals into verifiable predicates so that step-level, process-aligned rewards can train both levels. The look-ahead search uses success-probability pruning and value-informed scoring to focus data collection on promising branches, while closed-loop replanning prevents model error from cascading.\n\nThe self-sampled preference learning converts multi-step execution experience into shared-prefix comparisons, stabilizing updates to the high-level selector and propagating credit to early decisions. Finally, the adaptive, demonstration-seeded curriculum ensures that both skills and planner learn from solvable subproblems before tackling full tasks, accelerating convergence without sacrificing asymptotic optimality.",
