  "method": "We propose Bottleneck-Option Learning with Progress and Prototypes (BOLT), a three-stage hierarchy builder that turns long-horizon trajectories into a compact library of reusable subgoals and options, then trains a high-level controller to chain them efficiently. Stage 1 learns a lightweight progress scorer and core-subgoal selector. A shared state encoder maps states to embeddings; a self-supervised progress head is trained with temporal-order and masked-segment objectives to predict relative progress between two states. During rollouts or from a replay buffer, we compute per-step progress deltas and select a handful of core states per episode that most advance progress or sit on short paths to the goal in a growing transition graph. This yields a small set of candidate subgoal states that summarize each trajectory.\n\nStage 2 turns these candidates into a stable subgoal library via a prototype layer with uncertainty. We cluster core-state embeddings using a trainable set of prototype vectors; cosine similarity assigns each candidate to its nearest prototype, and an auxiliary uncertainty head flags low-confidence assignments. High uncertainty or low maximum similarity spawns a new prototype, while a group-sparsity regularizer on per-phase usage (phases given by coarse progress bins) prunes redundant prototypes and encourages specializing different options to different parts of the task. Each prototype defines an option: a low-level policy conditioned on the prototype embedding with a termination condition based on reaching high similarity to the prototype or timeouts.\n\nStage 3 trains the hierarchy with on-policy pseudo-supervision and a lightweight probabilistic prior. We construct and update a task graph over prototypes using observed transitions and a learned reachability/cost model. A pseudo-demonstrator plans one step ahead on this graph and, at each decision, proposes the next prototype that approximately minimizes distance-to-node plus node-to-goal. We mix these on-policy labels with the high-level policy’s choices using dataset aggregation to avoid distribution shift. A compact Bayesian network over subgoal dependencies provides a prior over the next prototype given the current prototype and context; it is trained with a sampling-based gradient estimator that avoids expensive full inference and is used to mask or reweight candidates during high-level selection. Low-level options optimize a shaped reward that blends true task reward with progress-to-prototype, and we apply hindsight relabeling so that reached prototypes become valid subgoal labels even when the intended prototype was missed.\n\nTraining follows a scaffolding curriculum. We begin with strong reliance on the pseudo-demonstrator and higher weight on progress shaping, then gradually anneal both so the high-level policy learns to pick prototypes autonomously and options complete them under sparse rewards. Throughout training, uncertainty-weighted updates maintain the prototype library: confident assignments refine prototypes with higher weight; persistently uncertain regions trigger option addition; prototypes with low usage under group sparsity are merged or removed. The result is a compact, phase-specialized option set and a high-level policy that composes them to solve long-horizon tasks.",
  "rationale": "Long-horizon credit assignment becomes tractable when decisions are evaluated at a slower temporal scale with meaningful subgoals. The progress-based selector identifies a handful of core waypoints that summarize each trajectory, dramatically shortening the effective planning horizon. Prototype-based clustering turns these waypoints into reusable, uncertainty-aware subgoals that double as option terminations, yielding stable, composable skills. Group-sparse screening keeps the option set small and phase-specialized, reducing interference and overfitting.\n\nOn-policy pseudo-labeling with a demonstrator fixes the classic distribution shift of offline hierarchy induction and supplies dense corrective signals to the high-level controller. The lightweight Bayesian prior injects inductive structure over subtask dependencies without incurring heavy inference costs, further accelerating exploration and choice at the high level. Finally, scaffolding—strong guidance and shaping early, annealed away later—provides a gentle optimization landscape that progressively hands credit from subgoal completion to the ultimate task reward.\n\nTogether, these components impose and learn a hierarchy that decomposes nested goals, shortens credit-assignment paths, and improves sample efficiency without relying on hand-labeled subgoals or expensive model-based planning.",
